MEMORANDUM
Re: Sentinel — AI-Assisted Credit Document Analysis for CRR Work Papers
Purpose
This memo describes Sentinel, an AI-assisted tool to support Credit Risk Review's independent assessment of investment banking credit documentation, and the efficiency case for adopting it across our review workstream.
What Sentinel Is
Sentinel is a credit document intelligence tool that extracts key evidence from credit documentation, structures it into standardized CRR work papers, and generates a preliminary, traceable assessment of borrower risk — covering repayment support, risk rating rationale, and adherence to review standards — while preserving human ownership of challenge, judgment, final ratings, issue identification, and formal reporting.
Specifically, it extracts the repayment-capacity narrative and supporting metrics; financials, liquidity analysis, adjustments, and projections; forward-looking cash flow analysis measured against plan; risk identification information and evidence of ongoing surveillance; and the elements supporting the PD, LGD, and regulatory risk rating.
How It Fits Our Workstream
Sentinel sits at the front of the independent review process as a standardization and acceleration layer. It captures the same core credit elements in the same structure on every review, so coverage of key analytical components is consistent across all reviewers, the captured evidence is equivalent review-to-review regardless of who performs it, every assertion is traceable to its source in the file, and potential risk signals are surfaced early to direct reviewer attention. The reviewer then validates, challenges, and owns the satisfactory/unsatisfactory conclusion and its rating impact. The future-state flow is: document ingestion → AI extraction and structuring → AI draft analysis → human validation and challenge → file memo.
Value Proposition
Sentinel enhances the efficiency, consistency, and coverage of CRR's independent review by systematically capturing and organizing the core evidence underlying credit risk assessments, while preserving human accountability for judgment and conclusions. It is not replacing analysts but augmenting them; not creating a new analytical framework but standardizing the existing one; and not removing control but improving consistency and audit availability. In short, it changes how consistently and traceably evidence is gathered and organized — not who is accountable for the judgment or the conclusion.
Efficiency and Resource Case
Methodology. The estimate deliberately draws on two datasets in distinct roles. A long-run baseline (2024–2026) establishes the effort required per work paper — approximately 27 hours — averaged across three years to smooth single-year variability and avoid overstating the opportunity. Actual 2025 IB review activity then supplies the real-world workload to which that rate is applied: 186 work papers completed across 6 reviews using 71 reviewer-assignments, with each review comprising a two-week fieldwork period. Because the 2027 book of work is not yet planned, 2025 serves as the most recent representative year for grounding the estimate in observed production.
Base case. Applying an AI-driven reduction of 10 hours per work paper lowers effort from 27 to 17 hours, raising reviewer productivity from 2.62 to approximately 3.9 work papers per person per review — a productivity lift of roughly 49%. Applied to 2025 review activity, this efficiency represents approximately $700,000 in annualized labor capacity created from the existing team, equivalent to roughly 3.9 full-time reviewers' worth of effort freed for redeployment.
What this enables. This is recovered capacity, not a staffing reduction. The same team is able to produce materially more with the time Sentinel returns to them. Concretely, the freed capacity allows the existing team to increase review throughput by approximately 50% — on the order of 90 additional work papers annually at constant headcount — directed toward broader portfolio coverage, deeper analysis on complex credits, or review of segments that current capacity does not reach. The value is realized as expanded and deepened review output rather than reduced effort.
